    facts:['Originally founded in the Young Town (Młode Miasto / Jungstadt), NOT the Old Suburb — a Teutonic-planned settlement north of the Old Town chartered c.1380','One of the six parishes established by Bishop Gruszczyński\'s 1456 decree, alongside St. Mary\'s, St. Catherine\'s, St. John\'s, Ss. Peter & Paul, and St. Barbara\'s','A \'wandering church\' — rebuilt in different locations after repeated destruction, one of very few Gdańsk churches to physically move','The Young Town was destroyed in 1455 during the revolt against the Teutonic Order; the church was rebuilt at its current location on zaułek Bartłomieja near the Old Town\'s northern edge','The current modest brick building reflects post-war reconstruction — far from the original medieval structure','Unusually small for one of the six canonical parishes, suggesting the Young Town\'s population was limited compared to the Main Town or Old Suburb'],
    relics:'Post-war reconstruction furnishings; Gothic architectural fragments preserved from earlier buildings',
    parishioners1500:'Originally served the Young Town\'s mixed population of craftsmen and labourers. After the Young Town\'s destruction in 1455, the parish served the northern periphery of the Old Town — tanners, dyers, and workers in less prestigious trades.',
    tax1500:'Low revenues — estimated 40–60 marks. Among the poorest of the six official parishes, reflecting its peripheral location and modest congregation.',
