    guilds:['Pomeranian Dukes','Cistercian Order'],
    organ:{has:true, year:1788, desc:'The celebrated Oliwa organ, built 1763–88 by Wulff & Dalitz — 7,876 pipes with moving angels and stars in the Rococo case. One of the most famous Baroque organs in Europe. Summer organ concerts draw thousands.'},
    facts:['107m long — actually longer than St. Mary\'s Basilica (105.5m)','Contains one of Europe\'s most famous Baroque organs (7,876 pipes, moving figures)','Oldest monastic foundation in the Gdańsk area (1186) — predating the Teutonic takeover','Survived WWII largely intact — the organ and Baroque interior preserved','Serves as the Archcathedral of the Archdiocese of Gdańsk'],
    relics:'Rococo organ with moving angels (1763–88); 23 Baroque altars; medieval tombstones of Pomeranian dukes; Gothic cloisters; Baroque paintings cycle; tombs of Cistercian abbots',
    parishioners1500:'Cistercian monks (community of ~40–60); servants and lay brothers; villagers of Oliwa settlement. The monastery owned extensive lands, forests, and fisheries supporting a large household.',
    tax1500:'The Cistercian monastery was one of the wealthiest landowners in Pomerania — revenues from vast agricultural estates, mills, fisheries, and forest rights far exceeded any city parish.',
    photoLinks:[
      {label:'Wikimedia Commons', url:'https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/Category:Oliwa_Cathedral_in_Gda%C5%84sk'},
      {label:'Wikipedia', url:'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oliwa_Cathedral'},
    ],
    sources:[
      {title:'Wikipedia: Oliwa Cathedral, Gdańsk', url:'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oliwa_Cathedral'},
      {title:'Famous Oliwa Organ — 7876 Pipes', url:'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oliwa_organ'},
      {title:'Oliwa Cathedral Museum & Summer Concerts', url:'https://katedra-oliwska.pl/en/'},
    ],
    events:[
      {year:1186, type:'founded',     label:'Cistercian monastery founded',      detail:'Cistercian monks from Kołbacz (Pomerania) founded a monastery in Oliwa, then a separate settlement north of Gdańsk. The Cistercians were invited by the Pomeranian duke Sambor I as part of the Christianisation of the region. This is the oldest monastic foundation in the Gdańsk area.'},
      {year:1224, type:'cornerstone', label:'First brick church begun',           detail:'The Romanesque-Gothic brick basilica was begun ~1224, making it one of the earliest brick churches in the region. The distinctive elongated plan (107m long — longer than St. Mary\'s Basilica) reflects Cistercian liturgical requirements for a large choir.'},
      {year:1350, type:'expansion',   label:'Gothic expansion completed',         detail:'The church was expanded into a full Gothic basilica with a long nave, transept, and elaborate chancel. The building became one of the longest churches in northern Europe at 107 metres.'},
      {year:1577, type:'destroyed',   label:'Burned during Batory siege',         detail:'During Stefan Batory\'s siege of Gdańsk (1577), the monastery and church were burned by Gdańsk citizens as a defensive measure to deny cover to besieging forces. Extensive rebuilding followed.'},
      {year:1594, type:'expansion',   label:'Baroque rebuilding after fire',      detail:'Major reconstruction gave the interior its predominantly baroque character, including new vaulting and furnishings.'},
      {year:1763, type:'expansion',   label:'Famous Rococo organ built',          detail:'The celebrated Oliwa organ was built 1763–88 by Jan Wilhelm Wulff and Johann Friedrich Rudolf Dalitz — with 7,876 pipes, moving angels and stars in the organ case, it became one of Europe\'s most famous Baroque organs and remains the cathedral\'s greatest treasure.'},
      {year:1831, type:'notable',     label:'Prussian dissolution of monastery',  detail:'Under Prussian secularisation, the Cistercian monastery was dissolved in 1831 after nearly 650 years of continuous monastic life. The church continued as a parish.'},
      {year:1925, type:'denomination',label:'Becomes cathedral — Diocese of Gdańsk', detail:'When the Diocese of Gdańsk was established in 1925 for the Free City of Danzig, the church was elevated to cathedral status — Katedra Oliwska.'},
      {year:1945, type:'notable',     label:'Survives WWII largely intact',       detail:'Unlike the city centre churches, Oliwa Cathedral survived WWII with relatively minor damage, thanks to its location several kilometres north of the main battle zone. The organ and baroque interior were preserved.'},
      {year:1976, type:'denomination',label:'Co-cathedral of Archdiocese',        detail:'When the Archdiocese of Gdańsk was created in 1992 (building on the 1976 restructuring), Oliwa Cathedral became the Archcathedral — the senior church of the archdiocese alongside St. Mary\'s as co-cathedral.'},
      {year:1992, type:'notable',     label:'Elevated to Minor Basilica',         detail:'Pope John Paul II designated Oliwa Cathedral a Minor Basilica, recognising its historical and architectural significance.'},
    ],
    denomBars:[{start:1186,end:2000,type:'catholic'}]
